    notes:
      "## Clinical Context — The Foundational Cardiovascular and Anti-Inflammatory Fatty Acid\n\nOmega-3 occupies a uniquely positioned role in foundational health supplementation — the supplement category with the strongest cardiovascular outcome evidence base (Vascepa REDUCE-IT trial pharmaceutical pedigree), substantial anti-inflammatory mechanism, and broad community familiarity.\n\nThe practical use case spans:\n\n**Foundational supplementation** — 1-2g combined EPA+DHA daily for cardiovascular and anti-inflammatory support\n\n**Anti-inflammatory optimization** — 2-3g combined EPA+DHA daily for users with chronic inflammatory conditions, autoimmune conditions, or general optimization\n\n**Triglyceride reduction** — 4g+ combined EPA+DHA daily (Vascepa-equivalent) for users with elevated triglycerides; coordinate with prescriber\n\n**Whole-food approach** — regular small fish consumption (sardines, anchovies, mackerel, herring, mussels) providing 1500-7000mg+ EPA+DHA depending on intake; superior bioavailability vs supplements; mercury-low species\n\n**Cardiovascular Lp(a)/ApoB context** — omega-3 is foundational support but not standalone Lp(a) intervention; users with hereditary lipid risk should layer omega-3 with comprehensive lipid management\n\n## The Form-Selection Hierarchy\n\n**For most users (general cardiovascular and anti-inflammatory support):**\n- **TG-form fish oil** (Nordic Naturals, Carlson Labs) — natural form, good bioavailability, moderate cost\n- **Re-esterified TG** (Nordic Naturals Ultimate Omega) — premium concentration with TG bioavailability\n\n**For high-dose triglyceride reduction:**\n- **Vascepa (icosapent ethyl)** — pharmaceutical, prescription, REDUCE-IT trial pedigree, 4g/day\n- **Concentrated EE-form fish oil** at 4g/day — non-prescription alternative\n\n**For users targeting SPM-specific effects:**\n- **SPM products** (Metagenics, Solutex) — direct supplementation; expensive; emerging evidence\n- **EPA-dominant supplements** at high dose — substrate for endogenous SPM production\n\n**For vegan/vegetarian users:**\n- **Algae oil** (Nordic Naturals Algae Omega, Ovega-3) — DHA-dominant; some EPA; mercury-free\n\n**For users prioritizing whole-food approach:**\n- **Small mercury-low fish** — sardines, anchovies, mackerel, herring, mussels — superior bioavailability vs supplements; the Wild Planet / Cole's / Bar Harbor product range provides convenient access\n\n## The ALA Conversion Reality\n\nALA (alpha-linolenic acid from flax, chia, walnuts) is the plant-based omega-3 precursor — but conversion to EPA (~5-10%) and DHA (<1%) in humans is poor. ALA is mechanistically inadequate as primary omega-3 source for users requiring EPA/DHA effects (cardiovascular, anti-inflammatory, brain). Vegan/vegetarian users requiring EPA/DHA should use **algae oil** rather than relying on ALA conversion.\n\n## The Lp(a) / ApoB Honest Framing\n\nUsers with hereditary lipid risk profile should approach omega-3 as foundational support rather than primary Lp(a) intervention:\n- **Triglyceride reduction**: substantial (20-50% at high doses)\n- **ApoB / LDL particle effects**: modest\n- **Lp(a) effects**: minimal (do not expect omega-3 to reduce hereditary Lp(a) elevation)\n- **Cardiovascular outcome (REDUCE-IT)**: significant in elevated-triglyceride context on statin\n\nFor hereditary Lp(a) management, modern interventions (PCSK9 inhibitors, RNA therapies — pelacarsen, olpasiran) are the principal approach with omega-3 as foundational adjunct.\n\n## Synergies\n**Vitamin E** — protects PUFAs from oxidation; standard pairing in fish oil products. **Vitamin D3** — combined foundational supplementation. **Magnesium** — broader cofactor support. **Astaxanthin** (krill oil contains; standalone available) — protects omega-3 from oxidation. **Comprehensive cardiovascular workup** for users with elevated CV risk profile.\n\n## Evidence Quality\nMechanism well-characterized; cardiovascular outcome evidence strongest among supplements (REDUCE-IT trial pharmaceutical pedigree); anti-inflammatory mechanism via EPA-derived eicosanoids and SPMs well-established; brain/retinal structural role of DHA established. Some negative trials (VITAL omega-3 arm, ASCEND) in unselected populations — benefit appears concentrated in users with elevated triglycerides or established CV disease.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: substantial mechanistic and clinical outcome evidence; REDUCE-IT trial CV outcome benefit at 4g icosapent ethyl; anti-inflammatory and brain/retinal mechanisms well-established; Lp(a) effects minimal. Anecdote: substantial integrative medicine and longevity community use base; community familiarity with TG vs EE form-selection; whole-food approach (Norwitz, ancestral nutrition community) increasingly recognized; the 'Dolphin Blood Diet' framing reflects emerging community framing of high-volume small fish consumption. Decision frame: foundational fatty acid with strongest cardiovascular outcome evidence among supplements; form-selection (TG vs EE vs whole-food) drives bioavailability; oxidation/rancidity is real quality concern; ALA conversion poor (use EPA/DHA direct); whole-food sources superior where dietary preference allows; the catalog does not provide specific protocol guidance per locked HRT/protocol rule.",
