    notes:
      "## Clinical Context — The Ratio Reframe\n\nOmega-6 occupies an unusual position in supplementation: the **most clinically important intervention is dietary reduction (industrial seed oils) rather than supplementation**. The 3:6 ratio framing — modern Western 20:1 vs ancestral 1:1-2:1 — is the principal hook for modern nutrition optimization, and the principal driver of the ratio distortion is industrial seed oil consumption (soybean, corn, sunflower, safflower, cottonseed) rather than insufficient omega-3 intake.\n\nThe practical use case spans:\n\n**Ratio correction (the principal intervention)** — reduce industrial seed oils (restaurant cooking, processed foods, packaged snacks, salad dressings); maintain or increase omega-3 from whole-food sources or supplementation\n\n**GLA-specific clinical supplementation** — cyclical mastalgia, atopic dermatitis, diabetic neuropathy, premenstrual symptoms; GLA 240-480mg/day from evening primrose or borage oil\n\n**Whole-food omega-6** — egg yolks, animal fats from grass-fed sources, nuts (walnuts, pine nuts) provide adequate omega-6 with healthier ratio profile than seed oils\n\n## The Seed Oil Framing\n\nIndustrial seed oils (soybean, corn, sunflower, safflower, cottonseed) are the principal driver of modern omega-6:omega-3 ratio distortion. These oils:\n- **Underwent industrial extraction** (high-heat, hexane solvent) introduced in the 20th century\n- **Replaced traditional fats** (animal fats, butter, lard) in restaurant cooking and processed foods\n- **Contain high LA** (~50-70% of fatty acid content)\n- **Are oxidation-sensitive** at cooking temperatures\n- **Are ubiquitous** in modern Western diet — restaurant cooking, processed foods, packaged snacks, salad dressings\n\nReducing industrial seed oil consumption is mechanistically the most consequential omega-6 intervention. Replace with: olive oil (omega-9 dominant), avocado oil, butter / ghee, animal fats from quality sources.\n\n## GLA-Specific Applications — When Supplementation Makes Sense\n\nGLA bypasses the rate-limiting delta-6-desaturase step (impaired in older adults, insulin resistant users, alcohol use history, magnesium/zinc deficient). Clinical contexts with evidence:\n\n**Cyclical mastalgia** — GLA 240-480mg/day; pairs with vitamin E (covered in this batch); 2-3 menstrual cycles for response; established RCT evidence base\n\n**Atopic dermatitis / eczema** — GLA modest evidence for skin barrier support\n\n**Diabetic peripheral neuropathy** — small RCT evidence base; mechanism via vascular and neural support\n\n**Premenstrual symptoms** — community use base; mechanism via series-1 prostaglandin support\n\n**Rheumatoid arthritis** — modest evidence; GLA supports anti-inflammatory eicosanoid production\n\n## Synergies\n**Omega-3** — paired ratio correction; the principal mechanism for modern dietary optimization. **Vitamin E** — protects PUFAs from oxidation; pairs with GLA for cyclical mastalgia. **Magnesium / zinc / B6** — cofactors for delta-6-desaturase; combined supplementation supports endogenous GLA production from LA. **Whole-food fats** — animal fats from grass-fed sources, olive oil, avocado oil provide healthier fat composition than industrial seed oils.\n\n## Evidence Quality\nMechanism well-characterized; ratio framing supported by mechanistic and epidemiologic evidence; GLA-specific clinical evidence base modest (cyclical mastalgia best-supported). Industrial seed oil reframe is increasingly mainstream nutrition recognition.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: foundational omega-6 biochemistry well-characterized; 3:6 ratio framing supported by mechanistic and epidemiologic evidence; GLA cyclical mastalgia evidence base modest but established. Anecdote: substantial integrative medicine and ancestral nutrition community use base; community familiarity with seed oil reframe (Saladino, Norwitz, ancestral nutrition community); cyclical mastalgia GLA + vitamin E protocol well-known. Decision frame: omega-6 is essential fatty acid but deficiency is essentially absent in modern populations; clinical issue is excess seed oil consumption distorting ratio rather than insufficient omega-6; principal intervention is dietary seed oil reduction rather than supplementation; GLA-specific supplementation appropriate for cyclical mastalgia and similar specific clinical contexts; the catalog does not provide specific protocol guidance per locked HRT/protocol rule.",
    tags: ["omega-6", "linoleic acid", "GLA", "gamma-linolenic acid", "evening primrose", "borage oil", "3:6 ratio", "seed oils", "cyclical mastalgia", "fatty acid"],
