    notes:
      "## Clinical Context — The Women's Health and Metabolic Underdog\n\nOmega-7 occupies a uniquely positioned role at the intersection of two distinct clinical contexts: **women's health (sea buckthorn for mucous membrane support, particularly postmenopausal vaginal dryness)** and **metabolic markers (Provinal purified palmitoleic for HDL/triglyceride/ApoB modulation)**. The two contexts use different products and different dose ranges; users should match form to clinical goal.\n\nThe practical use case spans:\n\n**Postmenopausal vaginal dryness / perimenopausal mucous membrane support** — sea buckthorn oil 3g/day for 3+ months; non-hormonal foundational support; coordinate with OB/GYN\n\n**Sjögren's syndrome / dry eye / broader xerosis** — sea buckthorn oil 1-3g/day; mucous membrane support broadly\n\n**Skin barrier dysfunction** — sea buckthorn oil 1-2g/day oral combined with topical preparations; atopic dermatitis, rosacea, broader xerosis\n\n**Metabolic markers (HDL, triglycerides, ApoB, hsCRP)** — Provinal 220mg/day OR sea buckthorn oil 1-2g/day; layered into broader cardiovascular support\n\n**Macadamia food source approach** — regular macadamia consumption provides meaningful palmitoleic acid without supplementation\n\n## The Women's Health Emphasis — Why Sea Buckthorn Matters\n\nPostmenopausal vaginal atrophy affects ~50% of postmenopausal women and produces symptoms (dryness, pain with intercourse, urinary symptoms, recurrent infections) that substantially impact quality of life. Standard interventions:\n- **Topical estrogen** — effective but contraindicated in some users (history of hormone-sensitive cancers, blood clots), inconvenient, requires prescription\n- **DHEA topical (Intrarosa)** — effective, prescription required\n- **Ospemifene oral SERM (Osphena)** — effective, prescription required, side effects\n- **Hyaluronic acid topical** — moderate evidence, accessible\n- **Sea buckthorn oil oral** — modest RCT evidence (3g/day x 3 months), accessible, no contraindications, foundational support\n\nFor users for whom hormonal interventions are contraindicated or undesired, sea buckthorn supplementation provides foundational mucous membrane support without hormonal mechanism. The traditional medicine use base (Russian, Mongolian, TCM) supports the biological plausibility; modern RCT evidence (Larmo et al., 2014; others) provides clinical validation.\n\nPepGuideIQ's user base includes women navigating perimenopause and menopause; sea buckthorn deserves catalog coverage as a meaningful non-hormonal option.\n\n## The Provinal Metabolic Markers Context\n\nProvinal (purified anchovy palmitoleic acid, Tersus Pharmaceuticals) at 220mg/day has demonstrated in small RCTs:\n- **HDL elevation** 5-15% (one of few interventions that meaningfully raises HDL)\n- **Triglyceride reduction** 15-25%\n- **ApoB modest reduction**\n- **hsCRP reduction** (anti-inflammatory marker)\n- **Lipoprotein particle effects** — emerging evidence\n\nEvidence base is preliminary — small RCTs rather than large CV outcome trials — but mechanistically interesting. Users with cardiovascular risk profile may consider Provinal as foundational support alongside comprehensive lipid management.\n\n## The Macadamia Nut Whole-Food Approach\n\nMacadamia nuts are the highest source of palmitoleic acid among common foods at ~20% of fatty acid content. Regular macadamia consumption (1-2 ounces daily) provides meaningful palmitoleic acid intake without supplementation, alongside other monounsaturated fats, vitamin E, magnesium, and broader nutritional benefits. This is a viable whole-food approach for users preferring food-source supplementation.\n\n## Synergies\n**Omega-3** — paired fatty acid pillar; combined cardiovascular and anti-inflammatory support. **Vitamin E** — fat-soluble antioxidant; protects PUFAs from oxidation; combined with sea buckthorn for skin/mucous membrane support. **Topical estrogen or DHEA** — coordinated with OB/GYN for postmenopausal vaginal atrophy. **Hyaluronic acid topical** — combined mucous membrane support.\n\n## Evidence Quality\nMechanism well-characterized via lipokine signaling research (Hotamisligil et al.); cardiovascular marker evidence from small Provinal RCTs preliminary; vaginal dryness sea buckthorn evidence from small but positive RCTs; mucous membrane support traditional use base substantial; skin barrier emerging evidence.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: lipokine signaling mechanism characterized; small Provinal RCTs supporting metabolic marker effects; sea buckthorn vaginal dryness RCT (Larmo et al., 2014) supporting postmenopausal applications; traditional medicine use base substantial. Anecdote: substantial integrative medicine and women's health community use base for sea buckthorn; Provinal less broadly known but established in cardiovascular optimization context; macadamia whole-food approach increasingly recognized. Decision frame: dual clinical contexts — women's health (sea buckthorn for postmenopausal vaginal dryness, mucous membrane support, skin barrier) and metabolic markers (Provinal purified palmitoleic for HDL/triglyceride/ApoB modulation); match product to clinical goal; sea buckthorn 3g/day for vaginal dryness clinical trial dose; Provinal 220mg/day for metabolic markers; macadamia nuts viable whole-food source; the catalog does not provide specific protocol guidance per locked HRT/protocol rule.",
